04355nam a22007215i 9780231502955DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999354255  a97802315029557 a10.7312/rock128902doi  a(DE-B1597)459272  a(OCoLC)940694281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBQ6331.K37R63 2003 7aPHO0140002bisacsh04a294.31 aRock, Sheila, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSera :bThe Way of the Tibetan Monk /cSheila Rock. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b113 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tPart 1 -- tPart 2 -- tPart 3 -- tPart 40 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTibet was once home to thousands of thriving Buddhist monasteries. But in 1959, following a Tibetan uprising against China's long occupation, nearly all were destroyed by the Chinese military, the practice of Buddhism was outlawed, and the Dalai Lama was forced into exile. In March of that year, Chinese tanks bombarded the 540-year-old Sera Jey Monastery in Lhasa, Tibet, killing hundreds of monks and destroying ancient texts and invaluable artifacts that had been collected over centuries. Thousands of survivors fled over perilous mountain passes to neighboring India, many with only thin robes and light footwear to shield them from the harsh winter conditions of the Himalayas.The Sera Jey Monastery, reestablished near Mysore, India, now houses 5,000 Buddhist monks living in exile-including many who escaped the attack on the Tibetan monastery in 1959, and many more who have never known their ancestral homeland. Providing an intimate glimpse of this rarely seen world, Sera: The Way of the Tibetan Monk evokes the subtle moods and rhythms of this Buddhist community that has steadfastly carried on the legacy of the original Sera Jey. More than 100 duotone photographs capture daily rituals and sacred ceremonies, serious moments and playful gestures, compassionate faces and expressions of inspired serenity. Moving and unforgettable, Sheila Rock's portraits celebrate the tranquility, simple joys, and unadorned beauty of the ascetic life, offering a powerful testament to the strength and resilience of a persecuted people. A percentage of the royalties from this book go to the Sera Jhe Health Care Committee in aid of various humanitarian projects  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aReligious life-Buddhism. 7aPhotography / Photoessays & Documentaries.2bisacsh1 aRock, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThurman, Robert A. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThurman, Robert.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/rock1289040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231502955423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231502955.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK